Data analysis

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.80) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.11. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 16.09 (S.E. = 2.92, p < .001, 95% CI [10.36, 21.82]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.05, S.E. = 0.05, p = 0.318, 95% CI [-0.05, 0.14]; Std. beta = 0.20, 95% CI [-0.19, 0.59])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -1.26, S.E. = 1.45, p = 0.386, 95% CI [-4.10, 1.59]; Std. beta = -0.36, 95% CI [-1.18, 0.46])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.18, S.E. = 0.81, p = 0.823, 95% CI [-1.40, 1.76]; Std. beta = 0.05, 95% CI [-0.40, 0.51])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 2.70, S.E. = 1.23, p = 0.028, 95% CI [0.29, 5.10]; Std. beta = 0.77, 95% CI [0.08, 1.47])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
